<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="542" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1123 Lincheng/187: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-06-29T13:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 29,
                                        1923—1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received June 29—7:53
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>242. Your 121, June 23, 3 p.m., last sentence. My 234, June 22, 10 a.m.
                            Major Allen has increased demand for indemnity in behalf of self, wife
                            and son to $150,000 gold.</p>
                        <p>Holcomb, formerly United States district attorney, Shanghai, who is
                            acting as counsel for four other American victims of Lincheng outrage
                            now in Shanghai has come to Peking to consult Legation regarding their
                            claims and informs me his clients intend to demand $150,000 gold each as
                            exemplary damages.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
